  "text": "The LuxR protein consists of two domains: the 88-aminoacid (aa) C-terminal domain (CTD), which is responsible for contacts of the protein with the lux box in DNA (the DNAbinding domain), and the 162-aa N-terminal domain (NTD), which determines its binding with the AI [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Here we tested the hypothesis that GroEL/GroES chaperonins are required for the folding of the NTD of LuxR.",
